TY  - JOUR
T1  - The characteristics of takeover targets q and other measures
AU  - Hasbrouck, Joel
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 9
IS  - 3
SP  - 351
EP  - 362
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(85)90038-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842668590038X
AB  - This study attempts to assess differences in the financial characteristics of target and non-target firms using logit analysis and a case-control methodology in which control groups are matched by size or industry. The results indicate that unregulated non-financial target firms are characterized by low q ratios (market/replacement values) and to a lesser extent high current financial liquidity. Measures of financial leverage were not found to be significant.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The dynamic behavior of business loans and the prime rate
AU  - Kling, John L.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 9
IS  - 3
SP  - 421
EP  - 442
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/09/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(85)90042-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426685900421
AB  - The purpose of this research is to determine the relevant variables, channels of influence, and dynamics characterizing the business-loan market. To achieve this goal the statistical approach of vector-autoregressive time-series analysis, popularized by Sims (1980, 1981) and Litterman (1979), is applied to a group of variables suggested by the portfolio and liability allocation problems of a representative bank and a representative business firm. The variance and historical decomposition analyses suggest that innovations in the level of business inventories and commercial bank financial assets are the most important casual variables in the business-loan market.
ER  - 

